            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is a debt-to-income ratio (DTI)?</h2>
              <p>
                Your debt-to-income ratio compares your monthly debt payments to
                your gross monthly income. Lenders use DTI to gauge how
                comfortably you can take on new debt such as a mortgage, auto
                loan, or personal loan.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Back-end DTI formula</p>
                <p>
                  \\[\text{Back-end DTI} = \frac{\text{Total monthly debt
                  payments}}{\text{Gross monthly income}} \\times 100\\]
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">
                  Front-end DTI formula (housing only)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \\[\text{Front-end DTI} = \frac{\text{Monthly housing
                  payment}}{\text{Gross monthly income}} \\times 100\\]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Front-end vs. back-end DTI</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Front-end DTI</strong> (housing ratio) includes only
                  your housing payment: mortgage or rent, property taxes,
                  homeowner's insurance, and HOA dues.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Back-end DTI</strong> (total DTI) includes housing
                  plus all other recurring monthly debts.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Debts typically included in DTI</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Mortgage or rent (plus taxes, insurance, HOA)</li>
                <li>Auto loans and leases</li>
                <li>Student loans</li>
                <li>Personal loans and lines of credit</li>
                <li>Credit card minimum payments</li>
                <li>Alimony or child support you pay (if court-ordered)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Everyday living expenses like utilities, groceries, childcare,
                and subscriptions are <strong>not</strong> usually counted in
                DTI, even though they affect your real-world budget.
              </p>

              <h2>What is a good debt-to-income ratio?</h2>
              <p>
                Guidelines vary by lender and loan program, but these ranges are
                common for back-end DTI:
              </p>

              <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                <thead>
                  <tr class="bg-gray-50">
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Back-end DTI
                    </th>
                    <th class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1 text-left">
                      Interpretation
                    </th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">&lt; 20%</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Very low debt load; strong capacity for new borrowing.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">20–36%</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Generally considered healthy and manageable.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">37–43%</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Often still acceptable, but lenders look more closely at
                      your profile.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">44–50%</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      High; some programs may still approve with strong
                      compensating factors.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">&gt; 50%</td>
                    <td class="border border-gray-200 px-2 py-1">
                      Very high; approval becomes difficult and risk of
                      financial stress increases.
                    </td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <p>
                For mortgages in the U.S., a back-end DTI of
                <strong>36% or less</strong> is often considered strong, while
                <strong>43%</strong> is a common upper limit for many “qualified
                mortgage” programs. FHA and VA loans may allow higher ratios
                with strong credit, savings, or other compensating factors.
              </p>

              <h2>How to improve your DTI</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pay down high-payment debts first.</strong> Target
                  loans or cards with large monthly payments; even small balance
                  reductions can improve DTI.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Avoid new borrowing.</strong> New auto loans, personal
                  loans, or “buy now, pay later” plans can quickly push your DTI
                  higher.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider refinancing or consolidating.</strong>
                  Extending loan terms or consolidating high-interest debt can
                  reduce monthly payments (though it may increase total interest
                  paid).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Increase your income.</strong> Side income, overtime,
                  or a raise can lower your DTI if the income is stable and
                  documentable.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Remove debts close to payoff.</strong> Paying off a
                  small remaining balance before applying for a major loan can
                  meaningfully improve your DTI.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and lender differences</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is a planning tool. Actual underwriting
                decisions depend on:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Loan type (conventional, FHA, VA, USDA, auto, personal, etc.)
                </li>
                <li>Credit score and credit history</li>
                <li>Down payment and assets</li>
                <li>Employment stability and income documentation</li>
                <li>Local and lender-specific overlays</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always confirm requirements with your lender or financial
                professional before making major decisions.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Does my DTI affect my credit score?</h3>
              <p>
                No, DTI itself is not a direct input into credit scoring models.
                However, high DTI often goes hand-in-hand with high credit
                utilization and missed payments, which <em>do</em> affect your
                score.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I use gross or net income for DTI?</h3>
              <p>
                Lenders almost always use <strong>gross income</strong> (before
                taxes and deductions). For personal budgeting, you may want to
                track a “net DTI” based on take-home pay, which is stricter and
                more conservative.
              </p>

              <h3>Are joint debts counted for both borrowers?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. If you are jointly liable for a debt, the full monthly
                payment is usually counted in your DTI, even if someone else
                helps pay it—unless you can document that another party has made
                the payments for a required period and the lender’s guidelines
                allow excluding it.
              </p>

              <h3>Can a high income offset a high DTI?</h3>
              <p>
                High income can help, but lenders still focus on the
                <em>percentage</em> of income going to debt. Very high earners
                may be allowed slightly higher DTIs, but there are still hard
                caps for many programs.
              </p>
